Step 1:  To find the intersection point $P$ on the line defined by $\begin{pmatrix} 1 \\ 2 \\ 3 \end{pmatrix} + t \begin{pmatrix} 2 \\ 3 \\ 4 \end{pmatrix}$, we can express point $P$ as $\begin{pmatrix} 1+2t_1 \\ 2+3t_1 \\ 3+4t_1 \end{pmatrix}$.
The equation of this line can be expressed as $\begin{pmatrix} 1 \\ 2 \\ 3 \end{pmatrix} + t \begin{pmatrix} 2 \\ 3 \\ 4 \end{pmatrix} = \begin{pmatrix} 1 \\ 2 \\ 3 \end{pmatrix} + \frac{t}{2} \cdot 2 \begin{pmatrix} 2 \\ 3 \\ 4 \end{pmatrix}.$
Step 2: $\begin{pmatrix} 1+2t_1 \\ 2+3t_1 \\ 3+4t_1 \end{pmatrix} = \begin{pmatrix} 1+2t \\ 2+3t \\ 3+4t \end{pmatrix}$
By equating the components of the two expressions for $P,$ we find $t_1 = t.$
Step 3: 
\begin{align*}
(1,1,1) &= (1+2t_1,(2+3t_1),(3+4t_1))\\
&= (1+2t,(2+3t),(3+4t))
\end{align*}
\begin{align*}
1&=1+2t\\
1&=2+3t\\
1&=3+4t
\end{align*}
\begin{align*}
2t&=-1\\
3t&=-1\\
4t&=-2
\end{align*}
## Step 4
\begin{align*}
t&=-\frac{1}{2}\\
t&=-\frac{1}{3}\\
t&=-\frac{1}{2}
\end{align*}
